Fireplace/reveal effects Pico project.

Default pins:
- GPIO 14: reset button to GND, using internal pull-up
- GPIO 15: PDLC smart film relay/driver input
- GPIO 16: smoke burst relay/driver input
- GPIO 17: fireplace puzzle solved input
- GPIO 18: electric lock relay/driver input
- GPIO 19: oven rotary encoder CLK
- GPIO 20: oven rotary encoder DT
- GPIO 21: oven rotary encoder SW

MQTT publish:
- escape/puzzle/fireplace/solved
- escape/puzzle/oven/solved
- escape/oven/degrees
- escape/post/cubby/4/state = ready or completed

MQTT commands:
- escape/pdlc/on
- escape/smoke/burst
- escape/lock/trigger
- escape/oven/enable
- escape/post/query
- escape/game/reset

When the local reset button is pressed, the Pico republishes its POST state.

The oven dial is enabled by the Raspberry Pi after every other puzzle is solved. The lock should open at the same time with escape/lock/trigger. The encoder is treated as relative; start the knob at 0/off before enabling, then turn to the configured 350-degree target.

The Pico publishes the current pretend oven temperature to escape/oven/degrees when the dial is enabled and every time the encoder moves. The Raspberry Pi stores the latest value so a display or LED feedback prop can be added later.

The lock output is pulsed for 100 ms by default so a spring-loaded dial compartment can release. Adjust OVEN_LOCK_RELEASE_MS in src/main.cpp if the lock hardware needs a different timing.

Use relay, MOSFET, or isolated driver modules. Do not switch mains power directly from Pico hardware.
